# Normalize line endings to LF everywhere (incl. Windows checkouts).
#
# Rationale: with Git-for-Windows autocrlf=true a fresh clone rewrites committed
# LF bytes to CRLF on checkout. That breaks goal-flight two ways:
#   (a) doctor's _sha256_file drift-check (goalflight_doctor.py) hashes file bytes
#       -> reports drift on EVERY file on a clean install; and
#   (b) the git-autoupdate clean-tree / ff-only gate sees the whole tree as dirty
#       -> auto-update silently skips forever (fails at its own purpose).
# Forcing eol=lf keeps byte-for-byte parity across platforms. After adding this
# file on an existing Windows clone, run once: git add --renormalize .
*               text=auto eol=lf

# Byte-hashed / line-ending-sensitive sources: force LF explicitly (belt + braces
# so every doctor-hashed file is covered regardless of auto-detection).
*.py            text eol=lf
*.sh            text eol=lf
*.md            text eol=lf
*.json          text eol=lf
*.txt           text eol=lf
*.yaml          text eol=lf
*.yml           text eol=lf
*.toml          text eol=lf
*.tpl           text eol=lf
*.cfg           text eol=lf
*.ini           text eol=lf

# Windows launchers: cmd.exe is the one interpreter that can mis-handle LF in
# batch labels/gotos, so keep .cmd/.bat CRLF. PowerShell tolerates LF.
*.cmd           text eol=crlf
*.bat           text eol=crlf
*.ps1           text eol=lf

# Binary assets: never touch.
*.png           binary
*.jpg           binary
*.jpeg          binary
*.gif           binary
*.ico           binary
*.pdf           binary
*.zip           binary
